    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid buildup during intense exercise, like HIIT, is a byproduct of anaerobic respiration, which is when your muscles run out of oxygen fast enough to meet the energy demands.  When the demand for ATP (energy) is high, your cells switch to glycolysis, which breaks down glucose into pyruvate. If oxygen isn't plentiful enough to process that pyruvate further in the mitochondria, it gets converted into lactate, which is what causes that burning sensation.\n\nThe body doesn't actually just \"clear out\" lactic acid; it converts it! Lactate is actually a fuel source, which is a very important distinction. Your liver and other tissues can take up this lactate and convert it back into pyruvate, which can then be used to create energy through the Krebs cycle, or it can be used to create new glucose in a process called the Cori cycle. So, it's more of a metabolic shuttle than just waste product.",
      "source": "target",
